<?xml version='1.0' encoding='UTF-8'?>
<ecoSpold xmlns="http://www.EcoInvent.org/EcoSpold02" xmlns:xsi="http://www.w3.org/2001/XMLSchema-instance" xsi:schemaLocation="http://www.EcoInvent.org/EcoSpold02 ../../schemas/datasets/EcoSpold02.xsd http://www.EcoInvent.org/UsedUserMasterData ../../schemas/datasets/EcoSpold02UserMasterData.xsd">
  <childActivityDataset>
    <activityDescription>
      <activity specialActivityType="0" id="99ab2bd2-eef6-5c6e-9078-9537f76c0d62" activityNameId="e2c4f7d7-ace0-4ba9-9a0d-afbbd4c4812e" parentActivityId="c88a163e-9759-45fd-a8ee-152c678f6683" inheritanceDepth="-1" type="1" energyValues="0">
        <activityName xml:lang="en">toluene diisocyanate production</activityName>
        <synonym xml:lang="en">Tolylene-2,4-diisocyanate</synonym>
        <synonym xml:lang="en">2,4-Toluene diisocyanate</synonym>
        <synonym xml:lang="en">2,4-Diisocyanato-1-methylbenzene</synonym>
        <includedActivitiesStart xml:lang="en">The activity starts when the raw materials enter the process.</includedActivitiesStart>
        <includedActivitiesEnd xml:lang="en">This activity ends once  the products, i.e., 1 kg of toluene diisocyanate and 0.86 kg of hydrochloric acid, are at the production site gate. Materials entering the process are included as well as energy uses, infrastructure and emissions.
</includedActivitiesEnd>
        <generalComment>
          <text xml:lang="en" index="0">This dataset represents the average production of 1 kg of toluene diisocyanate (TDI). At the same time, the formed hydrochloric acid is treated as a valuable by-product. This dataset was extrapolated from the European dataset (ISOPA, 2021), and thus the European average production technology was applied. </text>
          <text xml:lang="en" index="1">TDI (CAS: 584-84-9), an aromatic diisocyanate, is a white to pale yellow liquid with a pungent odour.TDI is mainly used in the industrial production of flexible polyurethane foams.</text>
          <text xml:lang="en" index="2">The industrial preparation of isocyanates is carried out with the reaction of an amine with phosgene in an aromatic solvent. In more detail, the production scheme for TDI can be breakdown into the following chemical reactions:</text>
          <text xml:lang="en" index="3">Nitration of toluene: C6H5CH3 + 2 HNO3 --&gt; C7H6N2O4 + 2 H2O</text>
          <text xml:lang="en" index="4">Hydrogenation of dinitrotoluene: C7H6N2O4 + 6 H2 --&gt; C7H10N2 + 4 H2O</text>
          <text xml:lang="en" index="5"></text>
          <text xml:lang="en" index="6">Toluene diamine phosgenation: C7H10N2 + 2 COCl2 --&gt; C9H6N2O2 + 4 HCl</text>
          <text xml:lang="en" index="7">Hence, toluene is the primary raw material for the production of TDI, while dinitrotoluene can also be used as a starting material, i.e., bypassing the nitration step.</text>
          <text xml:lang="en" index="8">This dataset is based on industry data from three different TDI producers with three plants in two different European countries, which participated in the data collection.</text>
          <text xml:lang="en" index="9">References:</text>
          <text xml:lang="en" index="10">Christian Six, Frank Richter (2011): Isocyanates, organic, Ullmann's Encyclopedia of Industrial Chemistry, Wiley-VCH.</text>
          <text xml:lang="en" index="11">Heino Falcke, Simon Holbrook, Iain Clenahan,Alfredo Lopez Carretero, Teoman Sanalan,</text>
          <text xml:lang="en" index="12">Thomas Brinkmann, Joze Roth, Benoit Zerger</text>
          <text xml:lang="en" index="13"> Serge Roudier, Luis Delgado Sancho (2017): Best Available Techniques (BAT) Reference Document for the Production of large Volume Organic Chemicals</text>
          <text xml:lang="en" index="14">2021, ISOPA , Eco-profile of toluene diisocyanate (TDI) and methylene diphenyl diisocyanate (MDI) , 3 - SeparatePublication</text>
          <text xml:lang="en" index="15">G. Margaret Wells, “Handbook of Petrochemicals and Processes”, 2nd edition, Ashgate, 1999</text>
          <text xml:lang="en" index="16">[This dataset is meant to replace the following datasets:]</text>
        </generalComment>
      </activity>
      <classification classificationId="4a11cbd4-74bf-47fb-9fe5-6e97e3db136b">
        <classificationSystem xml:lang="en">ISIC rev.4 ecoinvent</classificationSystem>
        <classificationValue xml:lang="en">2013:Manufacture of plastics and synthetic rubber in primary forms</classificationValue>
      </classification>
      <classification classificationId="3a73c9e2-b73a-41fb-9a63-9279f04c4582">
        <classificationSystem xml:lang="en">EcoSpold01Categories</classificationSystem>
        <classificationValue xml:lang="en">plastics/monomers</classificationValue>
      </classification>
      <geography geographyId="7846b897-7c04-4f9f-b607-2b83fcd9a74c">
        <shortname xml:lang="en">RoW</shortname>
        <comment>
          <text xml:lang="en" index="0">This dataset was extrapolated from the European dataset (ISOPA, 2021). Therefore, the European average production technology was applied. Representative 100% of European (EU-28) production of toluene diisocyanate.</text>
        </comment>
      </geography>
      <technology technologyLevel="3">
        <comment>
          <text xml:lang="en" index="0">This inventory represents the average production of toluene diisocyanate, provided as a generic dataset in which TDI production covers both (1) toluene and (2) dinitrotoluene as raw materials.</text>
          <text xml:lang="en" index="1">In more detail, the chemical processes involved in the TDI production are described below.</text>
          <text xml:lang="en" index="2">First, toluene, as the primary raw material for the industrial manufacturing of TDI, undergoes catalytic nitration, yielding approximately an 80:20 mixture of 2,4- and 2,6-dinitrotoluene (DNT) isomers. Hence, plants may start the production of TDI with either toluene or the respective mixture of DNT isomers. </text>
          <text xml:lang="en" index="3">Nitration of toluene: C6H5CH3 + 2 HNO3 --&gt; C7H6N2O4 + 2 H2O</text>
          <text xml:lang="en" index="4">A hydrogenation step follows, where the DNT mixture is converted to diaminotoluene (TDA) isomers.</text>
          <text xml:lang="en" index="5">Hydrogenation of dinitrotoluene: C7H6N2O4 + 6 H2 --&gt; C7H10N2 + 4 H2O</text>
          <text xml:lang="en" index="6"></text>
          <text xml:lang="en" index="7">The corresponding TDA mixture is subsequently treated with phosgene to produce a TDI isomer mixture in solution, along with HCl byproduct.</text>
          <text xml:lang="en" index="8">Toluene diamine phosgenation: C7H10N2 + 2 COCl2 --&gt; C9H6N2O2 + 4 HCl</text>
          <text xml:lang="en" index="9">In absence of phosgene in the form of a raw material, this intermediate is produced on-side from carbon monoxide and chlorine.</text>
          <text xml:lang="en" index="10">Phosgene production: CO + Cl2 --&gt;  COCl2</text>
          <text xml:lang="en" index="11">The solution is then purified via distillation, in which the 80:20 TDI isomer composition is maintained. Finally, a fractionation step is carried out, which yields a stream with 100% 2,4-TDI and another stream with a 65:35 mixture of 2,4- and 2,6-TDI isomers.</text>
          <text xml:lang="en" index="12">References:</text>
          <text xml:lang="en" index="13">2021, ISOPA , Eco-profile of toluene diisocyanate (TDI) and methylene diphenyl diisocyanate (MDI) , 3 - SeparatePublication</text>
        </comment>
      </technology>
      <timePeriod startDate="2020-01-01" endDate="2026-12-31" isDataValidForEntirePeriod="true">
        <comment>
          <text xml:lang="en" index="0">Data collection for production was collected as 12-month averages representing the year 2018. The inventory creation and calculation stage was concluded in 2020, while the technology is not expected to change until 2026.</text>
        </comment>
      </timePeriod>
      <macroEconomicScenario macroEconomicScenarioId="d9f57f0a-a01f-42eb-a57b-8f18d6635801">
        <name xml:lang="en">Business-as-Usual</name>
      </macroEconomicScenario>
    </activityDescription>
